HEADWORD: Stem
<hw>Stem</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>,

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stem
<hw>Stem</hw>,

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stem
<hw>Stem</hw> <pr>(st⟦ecr⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>stemn</ets>, <ets>stefn</ets>, <ets>staefn</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>stamn</ets> the stem of a ship, D. <ets>stam</ets> stem,
<ets>steven</ets> stem of a ship, G. <ets>stamm</ets> stem,
<ets>steven</ets> stem of a ship, Icel. <ets>stafn</ets>,
<ets>stamn</ets>, stem of a ship, <ets>stofn</ets>, <ets>stomn</ets>,
stem, Sw. <ets>stam</ets> a tree trunk, Dan. <ets>stamme</ets>. Cf.
<er>Staff</er>, <er>Stand</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The principal
body of a tree, shrub, or plant, of any kind; the main stock; the part
which supports the branches or the head or top.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>After they are shot up thirty feet in length, they spread a very
large top, having no bough nor twig in the trunk or the
<qex>stem</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lowering spring, with lavish rain,⟦br⟧
Beats down the slender <qex>stem</qex> and breaded grain.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A little branch which connects a fruit, flower, or
leaf with a main branch; a peduncle, pedicel, or petiole; <as>as, the
<ex>stem</ex> of an apple or a cherry</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The stock of a family; a race or generation of
progenitors.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧All that are of noble <xex>stem</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While I do pray, learn here thy <qex>stem</qex>⟦br⟧
And true descent.</q> <rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A branch of a family.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is a <qex>stem</qex>⟦br⟧
Of that victorious stock.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>A curved piece of timber to which
the two sides of a ship are united at the fore end. The lower end of it
is scarfed to the keel, and the bowsprit rests upon its upper end.
Hence, the forward part of a vessel; the bow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Fig.: An advanced or leading position; the
lookout.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wolsey sat at the <qex>stem</qex> more than twenty years.</q>
<rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>Anything resembling a stem or stalk; <as>as, the
<ex>stem</ex> of a tobacco pipe; the <ex>stem</ex> of a watch case, or
that part to which the ring, by which it is suspended, is
attached.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>That part of a plant which bears
leaves, or rudiments of leaves, whether rising above ground or wholly
subterranean.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The entire central
axis of a feather.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The basal portion of the body
of one of the Pennatulacea, or of a gorgonian.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The short perpendicular line
added to the body of a note; the tail of a crotchet, quaver, semiquaver,
etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>11.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>The part of an inflected word
which remains unchanged (except by euphonic variations) throughout a
given inflection; theme; base.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>From stem to stern</b></col> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>, <cd>from
one end of the ship to the other, or through the whole length.</cd> --
<col><b>Stem leaf</b></col> <fld>(Bot.)</fld>, <cd>a leaf growing from
the stem of a plant, as contrasted with a basal or radical
leaf.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Stem
<hw>Stem</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To remove the stem or
stems from; <as>as, to <ex>stem</ex> cherries</as>; to remove the stem
and its appendages (ribs and veins) from; <as>as, to <ex>stem</ex>
tobacco leaves</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To ram, as clay, into a blasting hole.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Stem
<hw>Stem</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Stemmed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Stemming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Either from <ets>stem</ets>,
n., or akin to <ets>stammer</ets>; cf. G. <ets>stemmen</ets> to press
against.]</ety> <def>To oppose or cut with, or as with, the stem of a
vessel; to resist, or make progress against; to stop or check the flow
of, as a current.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧An argosy to <xex>stem</xex> the
waves.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] <qex>stem</qex> the flood with their erected breasts.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stemmed</qex> the wild torrent of a barbarous age.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stem</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Stem
<hw>Stem</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To move forward against an
obstacle, as a vessel against a current.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Stemming</qex> nightly toward the pole.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stem-clasping</ent>⟦br⟧
